segments.text: and how you can be associated with them.
OK. Ready?
Yeah, I'm ready.
I don't have to do that.
Excuse me.
Well, my name is Paul W. Womack.
And I was born in Texarkana up in Bowie County in Northeast Texas, December 12, 1921, and lived there until I went into the Army during World War II.
I graduated from Texas Senior High School in Texarkana from Texarkana College, which was a junior college.

And for two years immediately preceding my entry into the United States Army in World War II, I worked at the Federal Correctional Institution in Texarkana, where I was secretary to the Classification Committee

responsible for history on responsible for recording the minutes of a committee that interviewed inmates coming in and got their life history and their health situation and the needs economic needs of their family at home so the so the prison could properly assign them to work duties and
give them the opportunity for educational and health facilities there at the prison.
I went into the Army in August of 1942, was overseas in October 1942, and spent three years in North Africa, Italy, and France, and returned.
I was with the Services Supply Army of the United States.
Primarily, I was a part of the various port headquarters at Casablanca.
Oh.
O-Ran, Naples, and Marseilles.
And we were in what was called the Transportation Corps.
Yeah.
Responsible for operating the port and, of course, receiving incoming cargo and personnel and seeing that it probably stored and then sent on to the front.
Were you an officer in this or an enlisted?
I went into the Army as a private in, uh, and while I was at Camp Robinson, which was a reception center at Little Rock, Arkansas, I was promoted to corporal first week because
because the brass found out that I knew how to type and take shorthand, which I learned in high school.
And they were extremely short of GIs with those capabilities, and they were preparing the forces at that time for the invasion of Europe, even at that point.
So I was promoted to corporal and then sent to...
Indian Town Gap, Pennsylvania, and from there to Staten Island, New York, and overseas to Casablanca within about two months after I joined the Army.
So you didn't go through a regular basic training?
No.

I was promoted to, I got various promotions and was promoted to warrant officer junior grade while still in North Africa, and then while I was in Italy, I received a field commission as second lieutenant after being thoroughly trained
questioned by a board of about 16 chicken colonels.
And I had that rank when I was discharged in 1945.
So as soon as I came back from the Army, I enrolled at Rice University to complete my undergraduate degree.
And after graduating from Rice with a liberal arts, bachelor of arts degree, I enrolled at South Texas College of Law, which is a night law school in Houston.
and graduated from there in 1950 with a Dr. George Prudence degree.

How I first came to know George Mitchell, some of this is going to be excess verbiage about me, and I don't want to take anything from the Woodlands, and you can cut all this out, but I do whatever you want.
I'd rather have more than that.
Yeah, I want you to understand how.
When I came to Houston in early 46 to enroll at Rice, I was planning to be married, and I needed a part-time job, because GI benefits were rather limited at that time.
I did go to school on GI, Bill, though, both at Rice University and South Texas College of Law.
This was in 46, you said?
Yeah.
Early 46?
Early 46.
You must have been one of the first ones separated out of it.
Yeah, well, see, the war ended in 45, and I arrived back home in, oh, I guess, November, October or November, went back to work for a brief period at the federal prison in Texas County.
Yeah, you would have had a lot of points then.
Oh, yeah, I did.
Oh, yeah, having been overseas for three years, I was one of the first to come back after the war in the Pacific ended.
And I needed to work, so I had a...

A friend I grew up with in Texas County who had married a young man who was down here in Houston and whom I did not know, but who was a student at South Texas College of Law and worked as a secretary in a small law firm in downtown Houston.
He didn't want to work but a half a day because he wanted his afternoons free to study for the night classes.
So through this acquaintance in Texas County to whom he had been married,

went down and got on as a part-time secretary to the law firm in downtown Houston and worked there in the afternoons and later on full-time all the way through Rice University and South Texas College of Law.
In that law firm was Paul Smith, an attorney, now retired, who had known George and Johnny Mitchell.
They grew up together in Galveston.
They were all BOIs.
I know you're familiar with that phrase.

So at that time, George and Johnny and Merlin and a fellow by the name of Roxy Wright were just beginning, that's early 46, were just beginning to get into the oil business with offices over in the Esperson building in downtown Houston.
So I was secretary to Paul Smith and the other lawyers in the firm.
They were free, I guess, at that time.
And Paul was doing George and Johnny's oil and gas work at the very beginning when they got into the oil business.
So that's when I met George Mitchell and Johnny in early 1946.
But when I graduated from law school, I had made commitments to go with the same
young man who had graduated from law school and entered the title business in Houston, so I went into practice with him.

I didn't become associated again with Paul Smith of the firm of Smith and Fulton, who were attorneys all through the formative stages of the Mitchell Company and on until Paul retired and Tom Fulton passed away about two or three years ago.
Let me see, I've lost my train of thought.

I became associated with Paul Smith and Tom Fulton in early 1964, at the very time that George was in the process of completing the acquisition of the Old Grove and Copper and Lumber Company, which owned several thousand acres of land in Montgomery and the joining counties.

Most of my work during that period when I was not associated with Paul or the Mitchell Companies in any way was in the real estate field as attorney for a title company and doing real estate conveyancing and primarily that's what I was doing in private practice.
Was that more or less your specialty?
Yes, that was my specialty, real estate.
So it just fell into place there for about three or four years as they began to get into the real estate business.
They had been, of course,
only in the oil and gas and related businesses up to that time in 64.
And it just fell in line that I was doing some of the Mitchell work while I was associated with Smith and Fulton, not as a partner, but just an associate.
And so the company offered me the position of vice president and counsel on effective January 1, 1968.
And that's when I became an employee of the Mitchell Company's
And at that time began the creation of the legal department.
Mitchell never had an internal legal department.
As such, they had this small firm of Smith and Fulton, which served as a sort of in-house law department.
But they were not integrated as a part of the company.
And that was the beginning, and I worked with,
Mr. Charles Lively, who was employed by the company and who was the outside contact between the company and various property owners in the Woodlands area.
And at that time, I was the legal department for a couple years or so at Mitchell.
I had one secretary.
And Mr. Mitchell, of course, would make the decisions as to what properties he wanted to acquire in connection with
blocking up this land out here for the Woodlands development, and Charles would make the contact with the owners and bring back the information, and I would write the contracts.
We probably, I guess we must have had 300 or more separate transactions all the way down from a half acre up to several thousand acres of land involved in the various transactions that were
entered into in order to block up the land, the woodlands.
Were there any special legal challenges associated with that?

Well, there were a number of special challenges, and later on, David Bumgardner, who's now Associate General Counsel and heads the Real Estate Department, or Division of the Legal Department, Dave came to work for me in the legal department, and he became involved with me in a number of challenging
transactions, one of which was an exchange of land with Champion.
Lumber company?
Yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah, Champion.

And they had a they had a subsidiary called Champion Realty, I believe, and very complicated process of working out an exchange of some land that they had for some land we wanted in the closer proximity to the core of the woodlands.
And that turned out to be quite a challenging situation.
And then Mr. Mitchell decided that he would like to get into the land title insurance business.
So it was Dave and my responsibility to get all the title work done for the several thousand acres that then comprised the woodlands.

and get it ready not only for the entrance into the title business, which we did before we had sold the bonds to start the Woodlands, but also to have a title insurance agency that we were part owners of that would be writing the title insurance here in the Woodlands.
Do you know what prompted Mr. Mitchell's decision to get into the title business?
Well, Leonard Ivins at that time, who came down from Baltimore, Maryland,

uh was head of the woodlands and he i think lynn more than george wanted to capture as much of the business that was created by the woodlands development that he could and including that he knew was quite a bit of title business and he thought was uh probably very lucrative so i think it was lynn ivan's more so than george himself but george readily agreed to it and
One thing that happened, we started out with one company and were pressed for time.
This was in early 72.

And, of course, George had another friend on at Galveston, Carlos Morris, who was president, chairman of Stewart Title Guarantee Company, which is the granddaddy of Title Insurance in the state of Texas.
So almost at the 11th hour, Carlos Marsh talked George into going to the Stewart Title Guarantee Company in the development of the title business in the Woodlands.
So we had to switch gears.
And of course, we had worked with Stewart in other areas, like especially down at Galveston in the Pirates Cove and Pirates Beach subdivisions down there.
And we knew all those people.
But we switched gears and got the company started, which is now
stir a title of Montgomery County, Inc. here in the Woodlands.
And that proved to be quite a challenge.
And getting the titles of all of the land involved in the Woodlands ready to be in an insurable status so that the bonds could be issued.
And what we had to do was, pardon me, just for me, sir.
What did I say, Donovan?
You were in the process of getting all the titles together for the bonding?
Oh, yeah, because the bonds were guaranteed by the United States government.
And to secure that guarantee, we had to give the government a deed of trust on all of the land out here.
And necessarily all of the parcels had to be examined and surveys made and exceptions noted, reservations, and all of that.
in order for stirred title guarantee company to issue the $50 million policy guaranteeing, ensuring that the titles were good and that the that the lean was good.
So we had to do this under a pressure situation.
In fact, Dave and I worked in New York for two days with a total of about six hours sleep, three hours each night getting that ready.
And we in order to
to have it ready before the bonds were sold in late summer, early fall of 1972.
That proved to be quite a challenging operation, too.
Can you imagine how many pieces of land were involved in the 25,000 acres out here at the Woodlands and all the mineral exceptions, easements, and everything else?
And there were a number of titles which had to be cleared up.
Most of which, though, were just a simple matter, not too many complicated title requirements that had to be curated.
To make a long story short, we did get the information ready so that the policy could be issued in time for the sale of the $50 million in bonds.
And that was a negotiated sale, and time was a big factor there, too.
Because I think, if I'm not wrong, this was the last negotiated

bond sale that they had from then on they decided to go out to bid process and we got a as a result of that we got a very favorable 7.1 interest rate and then uh later on uh mr mitchell wanted to sell uh some of the timber on the various tracks of land some of the pine timber in georgia pacific
was then active in this area.
Later on, Louisiana's Pacific was spun off of Georgia Pacific because of antitrust problems with the government.
But we had to prepare the initial contract under which 100 million board feet of pine timber was sold.
And I'd never drawn a timber contract in my life up to that point.
And that was a very challenging situation by virtue of the fact that I had studied typing and shorthand in high school and worked with it all through the Army, my Army experience.
And while I was working in prison in Tuxcana, I became a pretty good typist.
And I would work on the contract at night at home and bring it back, and we'd review it during the day with all the representatives of Georgia Pacific and
and our people that furnished, of course, the technical information necessary to prepare the agreement.
And we got that worked out, which is, you know, even to this day is used as the landmark contract for dealings with Louisiana Pacific.
And then another challenging opportunity for me came when the attorney that Lynn Ivins had

employed up in Baltimore that he had known at the Roush development up there to to work out the terms of a contract with Gulf States Utility Company to provide electric power to the woodlands and also to to pay a sort of not really a license fee because we were not a city and not in a position to give a license was very comparable to
a fee that they would pay the city of Houston, for instance, like Houston Lighting Power, for a license to operate.
Now, who are they?
This was in Gulf State, isn't it?
Gulf State Utility Company, yes.
And they still, of course, they're the only utility company serving the woodlands.
And along the way, Lynn became disenchanted with this lawyer up there, and he was
charging what he considered an excessive fee, so he asked me to pick up the ball and continue with that, which we did.

We finally reached an agreement with Gulf States Utilities Company, and it's, of course, still the contract under which Gulf States provides electric power and pays a royalty or fee to the woodlands, which is used to help pay community, cost of community amenities.
Could you also get involved in...
the other utilities?
No.
Dave worked out, Dave Baumgartner worked out, did most of the work on the agreement with, I believe, to set up a gas company here in the Woodlands, which was later sold to Intex early on.
We had to do it initially because we had to have gas to provide the customers, you know, the residents out here, and we set up our own gas company, which was later.
I did some work on that, but
It was later sold to Intex, and I think John Watson, who's in governmental affairs, he's probably one of the people on your list.
He worked on the negotiations with Intex, and Dave and I did the legal work to sell that gas company to Intex.
Why did they sell it?
That seems, well, it's a different,
It's a related kind of industry.
Well, it's related, but that was the only entry into the retail utility business that the company had until they got into the cable television business later on.
And for some reason or other, Mr. Mitchell just didn't want to continue that particular business and made the deal with Intex.
Of course, they're now the provider of natural gas.

here in the woodlands what about the water water of course is provided by a series of municipal utility districts created and there again dave bungardner did most of the legal work on assisting with creation and a lawyer here who's on the outside of the county mike page represented the the district's uh
as they were created and the necessary legal work with the state to get them created and get the bond issue authorized and sold.
Each MUD has its own bond?
Yes, each MUD has its own bond.
Each MUD has its own officers and trustees, and they serve a certain designated area just like a school district would.

and they they use common facilities a lot out here common sewer treatment plants through contract and that type of thing but they're all individually created districts with taxing authority and and the responsibility of providing water sewer and drainage to the area within their respective boundaries and the telephone situation proved to be a kind of a sticky situation we had

again i think mr ivan's was probably more the moving factor in the creation of the telephone business than was george but of course george went along with it and we we formed a company in partnership with a with a company up in kylene i think it's called central telephone or something like that and uh we were going to own and and the telephone local telephone company here in the woodlands well we got
We got into a situation where Southwestern Bell refused to give the company tie-ins for long-distance service.
When was this?
Oh, the very early days of development.
In the early 70s?
Yeah, yeah.
And what we would have had, had we continued that, would have been just a giant intercommunication system here in the woodlands with no interconnects with long-distance.
So the company hired some lawyers in Houston.

Louis Payne primarily did the trial work and sued the Southwestern Belt Telephone Company under the antitrust laws for refusing to give interconnects and making it impossible, really, for the company which we had formed to install and operate a telephone system here in the woods.
It was a 50-50 deal.
We brought to the table, of course, the Woodlands and the business, and the other company brought to the table the expertise and know-how in operation of a telephone company.
But we tried that case in the federal court in Houston, and we got a judgment from the jury for everything we asked for.
This was, again, about the 70s?
Yeah, it was in the early 70s.
It must have been, well, I'm sure it was after we
had opened in 74, probably middle or later latter 70s that this occurred.
And we filed suit.
And like I said, we got a judgment.
The jury rounded it off and lopped off $0.60 of the amount we
we sued for.
But other than that, they gave us everything we sued for.
And under federal law, antitrust judgments are tripled.
Whatever you get from the jury is tripled.
So the judgment was $54 million in excess of $54 million.
Well, naturally, the telephone, Southwestern Bell, appealed it.
And the case was overturned by the Fifth Circuit in New Orleans in a ridiculous opinion.
But nevertheless, they did overturn it.
And after that, we settled with Southwestern Bell.
They came into the woodlands, and that's why we have Southwestern Bell's AT&T system now instead of our own woodlands telecommunications system.
Part of the settlement was cash, and part of the settlement was they purchased some land here in the woodlands.
And we got a fairly nice settlement, but nothing like the
the judgment of $54 million.
So this other communications telephone company by the wayside.
Doesn't exist.
Doesn't exist.
Although that used to be a norm in Texas.
Yes.
People did that.
In fact, there's two of them in Lubbock or something like that.
Well, I think there's one over here at Kingwood, too.
And for some reason or other, they were able to get the necessary interconnects, but we couldn't.
They just flat wouldn't work with us at all.
I guess they saw the potential for business here in the Woodlands and wanted it, of course, for themselves.
That's interesting.
Tell me, you mentioned earlier about a cable company that Mr. Mitchell put together.
I'd never heard about that.
Well, we started the Woodlands Cablevision Company and operated it for a number of years.

And I believe the company, the sale of 50% of it occurred after I retired, but I think it's still, in fact, I'm sure the company still owns 50%, but it's managed by the company that bought the other 50% interest in it.
But for many years, we operated, owned and operated 100% of all the cable television services here in the Woodlands.
Was this, I mean, obviously the intent was to make money, but also was it a quality of life issue?
Well, yes, yes.

I noticed Mr. Mitchell seemed very, very savvy about... Yeah, he wanted not only the services that cable companies can provide, but also the availability of local channels for local programming and things that would benefit the people living in the woodlands.

educational services and things of that nature because he's been an ardent supporter of kuh tv oh yes channel nine uh channel uh eight eight yeah yeah public television yeah okay yeah but that's a regular that's a regular commercial public not commercial but it's a regular public television station this is just the cable that serves the woodlands yeah right now called woodlands cable vision i forgot what we called it when when did that company
Well, I would say that company was formed very early, Don.
But of course, I could research these things and get the dates and everything.
Mike Richmond, over in the Executive Vice President of Woodlands Corporation, could fill you in on more detail.
Mike was more directly involved in that.
We've talked with him, but none of this came out.
It didn't?
Well, we didn't know what to ask.
Yeah.
Well, he was more interested in the woodlands, per se.
Yeah.
But one of the things that has intrigued me is the... One of the things I find fascinating about the woodlands is the completeness of the vision, the...
maybe those are poor terms, but the comprehensiveness, maybe, of the vision that Mr. Mitchell had, which seemed to cover every aspect of... That came, of course, from George Mitchell.
Mike was one of the people we got from the Roush folks out at Baltimore.
And another man that we had here who passed away about two years ago, Byrne Robbins, was responsible for a lot of the early development of the woodlands.

and we had some other other fellows here but mike i believe is about the only one that remains from that group as an executive ordinance corporation you returned in 86 february of uh 87 february 1st 87. four years will be four years has come in february since uh that book was published six seven years ago what what changes have you seen
in the woodlands and the directions it's going?
Well, of course, there's been considerable increase in commercial activity in the woodlands, the development of the research forest.
I was involved in the initial legal work done when HARC was created.
In fact, I drew the original
proposal between the company and Skip Porter, who's now president of Hark.

Because George, when he wanted to keep things pretty much close to the chest, he would just call me into his office, and I'd bring my shorthand pad, and he would, if I hadn't been able to take shorthand, I wouldn't have been able to keep up with him.

and he'd dictate the terms of the agreement, you know, and then I'd take it back and prepare the agreements, and I worked with him and with Skip Porter on that when Skip was at A&M, where he came from here.
I haven't had much to do with Hark since then, but was very much involved in the early creation of it.
and the increase, of course, in the educational facilities here in the Woodlands, and building of new schools, and also in the church activity.

I'm a member of the First Baptist Church here in the Woodlands, which was the first church created in the Woodlands, and since then there have been numerous churches, and some of them are getting quite large.
The idea we had, or the idea Mr. Mitchell had initially, just didn't fly, but it was a very good idea, and his idea was that

Instead of every denomination or congregation building a separate building, which they would use probably just a fraction of the time each week and on weekends, his idea was to have a common facility that would be used by numerous different denominations and therefore really save a lot of money in building independent churches.
The idea just never seemed to catch on.
So we have churches of just about every denomination, I believe, here in the Woodlands now.
And of course, that's been progressing ever since the Woodlands was formed, not necessarily in the last three or four years.
I still do some work for Mr. Mitchell.
And of course, I still keep up with what's going on here, even though I don't do legal work for the company.
But I think that in the near future,

We're going to see continued development in the research forest area, and that's where I think the Woodlands probably will make the greatest input in the business and industrial and governmental and educational combination.
Well, the regional mall.
Yes, and the regional mall will come.
And the mall, not the mall, but the other shopping center above the mall, between the mall and the hospital,
I think the Target store is scheduled to open in the fall of this year, so that will be good for that area up there.
And numerous new parks are being created, which is good.
I think we'll have excellent golf courses and public parks.
It's still a unique development insofar as everything that it offers its residents.
not the least of which is security, and which is very important nowadays.

Did you get involved, I can't remember who it was now, someone mentioned that a few years ago, or actually when Mr. Mitchell was trying to get this started, there was some resistance from the part of the, well, the county commissioners.
Montgomery County was, you know, kind of... Well, yes, I was aware of that.
And also, of course, I was involved in working with the outside law firm that we employed to work with the city of Houston in extending its territorial jurisdiction to include the woodlands.
And I think probably in the background, the problems with the Montgomery County officials might have been responsible for that as much as anything.
plus the fact that we did not want the city of Houston out here.
We didn't want these small municipalities growing up out here like you see out in Memorial Drive, for instance.
And in order to do that, we asked the city of Houston to extend its extraterritorial jurisdiction under Texas law, which Houston did, of course.
And then along the way, we had to file a suit against Shenandoah because they ran a strip down the freeway, and they were trying to annex everything down to and including the area where the mall was.
And we hired Will Sears' firm.
Will just passed away the other day.
Will Sears' firm, Sears and Burns in Houston, and filed suit and finally worked that out with Shenandoah.
Involved in it was the location of the Woodlands Hospital and some other things.

we got their their boundaries pushed north of the of the of the mall area where the new target pinecraft center would be what was the what was the motivation for that were they just trying to grab i think they were just trying to expand the city and and expand their tax base and they could foresee the development and the increase in value along the freeway there in particular but but their annexation
strip description was erroneous for one thing.
That was the basis on which the suit was filed.
We have very good relations with the city of Shenandoah now, as far as I know.
Excellent relations with them.
One of the most unusual acquisitions, I guess, going back to the time when we were blocking up land, was the acquisition of this frontage on the freeway.
It belonged to
two different groups.
One had an undivided half interest and another family group had the other one.
We acquired the first undivided half interest with very little trouble, but the second remaining undivided half interest belonged to a Waco banker we called Robert Mann, by the name of Robert Mann.
He had banking interests in Waco and several other Texas cities.
And we negotiated with him
Labor Day, I believe it was, in 72, because we naturally wanted that land.
We wanted his undivided half-interest.
And we negotiated with him one Labor Day while he was trying to push us and pressure us because he had to catch a plane for Washington.
And I had to call George back to the woodlands from Galveston where he was on his weekend vacation down there.
And so before the day's end, though, we worked out a deal whereby we acquired
It amounted to net 2,000 acres.
That's what it amounted to.
It divided half inches in 4,000 acres of land along the freeway.

And initially, another interesting thing to me is that initially we thought that Woodlands Parkway, what's now Woodlands Parkway, would have some commercial development along the sides, like the traditional strip centers down along 1960 and other places.
And initially we had planned to do that.
And but that idea was abandoned in favor of concentrating the commercial development in the neighborhoods and then the major commercial development along the freeway.
But that was our initial plan.
There's been some discussion, argument even, maybe.
Well, maybe that's too strong a term.
But at least discussion about the wisdom of doing that.
Because from the freeway, all you see is a wall of trees.
And it's sort of like, what's the woodlands?
I mean, it's almost a secret blend

you know and uh there was some some comment made by by some of the individuals we've talked to that um maybe the woodlands would have been a lot better off if they would have knocked down a few of those trees and as you could see into one of those lakes at least yeah you know as sort of a come on or an intriguing kind of uh well mr mitchell from the very outset has been very protective i know that's why there's a lot of knowledge
Not only the trees, but the vegetation, you know.

In fact, it took years before Roger Gladys was successful in clearing the intersections because the growth of the undergrowth and the trees and everything at intersections had begun to be a traffic hazard.
Yeah, you couldn't see.
We had several.

And I don't know whether Mr. Mitchell ever totally agreed with him or not, but I do know that I was noticing this morning, as a matter of fact, as I came down off of Grogan's Mill Road onto Timberlock Place
how much different it looks now from what it used to.
And I think it's an improvement, not only aesthetically, but from a traffic safety standpoint.
But I doubt if George ever wholly bought that idea because he loves those trees and those wildflowers and that underground.
You live here in the woods?
Yes.
I live over here on Log Run Circle, just back of the country club.
My wife and I moved out here in December of 79, just about a year before the company headquarters moved out here.
So you, now this isn't, because not everyone in the Woodlands Company even lives in the woodlands.
No, that's true.
And, but you bought?
I bought a house out here in early 79, knowing that the company was, you know, in the process of moving out here, and rented it for a while, and then moved into it in December of 79.

I had trouble getting my wife out here because we'd been living for twenty years in Southwest Houston where all her friends, all the professional people that she used, and the church was four or five blocks away.
It took me two years to find a house.
But she's one of the greatest proponents of the Woodlands now, and she just loves the place.
That's been a consistent problem.
The Woodlands has
a very keen, natural kind of environment.
But I noticed that there's been several people who expressed concern that, you know, my gosh, what would my wife do here?
I seemed isolated from whatever.
This was a real problem.
You know, I considered every possible alternative, commuting every day, which would have been an 80-mile round-trip commute from where we lived out near the Astrodome.
And...
Even renting an apartment and living out here the week and going back home on the weekends, but nothing seemed to really be the way to go.
But finally, I found the house that she and I both fell in love with, and she has never been sorry that we moved out here.
Wonderful place to live.
The pavilion actually happened after you retired, didn't it?
Well, let me ask you, this is sort of a standard question we've asked everyone.
Let's see if that other one comes back to my head.
It is obvious that the Woodlands Corporation has a culture that is unique, and the majority of that uniqueness comes from the personality of George Mitchell.
Or a lot of it.
At some point,
Mr. Mitchell's presence in the Woodlands Corporation won't be either as strong or won't be there at all.
He'll pass on, just as we all will.
What do you foresee happening when that eventuality becomes a reality?
That's a very difficult question.
First, I don't like to think about it even, about him not being here, because having known George since 1946 and having worked with him about
half of that time.
I just can't foresee his vision and his ideas continuing, although we've got some very good people in the Woodlands Corporation.

And I think, though, that with the impetus that's developed already, and which will continue, of course, as long as he's here, I think it will continue to be the development that it was originally planned to be, which was about a city of about 150,000 people.
with diversity of residential construction so that we could avoid in the woodlands what's happened in every major city in the country, the inner city slums and that type of thing.
And that idea has caught on out here, and it's worked very satisfactorily.
And I think certainly that it would be sad indeed if whoever
takes over the Woodlands Corporation didn't continue that throughout the total acreage yet available for development.
And the recreational facilities available to the residents and to the public in general out here are the finest in the land.

I don't know of anything it even compares that I've been to unless it's Hilton Head, and I think we're rapidly passing Hilton Head because I haven't been to some of the ones in Florida and California, but
